            "title": "Gold Peaks Over $3,900/oz as Investors Grapple With Shutdown -- Market Talk",
            "description": "<div class=\"txt-s4 article-text\"><p>\n  Gold futures have peaked over the $3,900 per troy ounce mark again this week, with the most-active contract up 0.9% to roughly $3,902/oz. China is in the midst of their Golden Week period for its National Day holiday, which typically slows down the demand for physical gold on a global scale. But the U.S. government shutdown has injected fresh demand for precious metals as a safety hedge, says Ole Hansen of Saxo Bank. \"The usual risk of a pullback during China's Golden Week, when physical demand tends to ease, has not yet emerged,\" says Hansen in a note. Silver is also up, rising 3% to $47.77/oz and climbing towards the all-time record from 1980. (kirk.maltais@wsj.com) </p><br/><p>\n  (END) Dow Jones Newswires</p><!-- Article --><p>\n\n  10-03-25 1121ET</p></div>",
            "link": "https://hk.marketscreener.com/news/gold-peaks-over-3-900-oz-as-investors-grapple-with-shutdown-market-talk-ce7d5bdfdd81f622",
